04026nam a22005655i 9780226427201DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264272017 a10.7208/97802264272012doi  a(DE-B1597)524498  a(OCoLC)973406068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aMikhail, Alan, eauthor.10aUnder Osman's Tree :bThe Ottoman Empire, Egypt, and Environmental History /cAlan Mikhail. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b17 halftones, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Osman's Tree -- tIntroduction: The Global Environmental History of the Middle East -- tPart One: Water -- t1 Irrigation Works -- t2 History from Below -- t3 Silt and Empire -- tPart Two: Work -- t4 Rural Muscle -- t5 Expert Measures -- tPart Three: Animal -- t6 Animal Capital -- t7 Brute Force -- tPart Four: Elemental -- t8 Food and Wood -- t9 Plague Ecologies -- t10 Egypt, Iceland, SO2 -- tConclusion: Empire as Ecosystem -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOsman, the founder of the Ottoman Empire, had a dream in which a tree sprouted from his navel. As the tree grew, its shade covered the earth; as Osman's empire grew, it, too, covered the earth. This is the most widely accepted foundation myth of the longest-lasting empire in the history of Islam, and offers a telling clue to its unique legacy. Underlying every aspect of the Ottoman Empire's epic history-from its founding around 1300 to its end in the twentieth century-is its successful management of natural resources. Under Osman's Tree analyzes this rich environmental history to understand the most remarkable qualities of the Ottoman Empire-its longevity, politics, economy, and society.   The early modern Middle East was the world's most crucial zone of connection and interaction. Accordingly, the Ottoman Empire's many varied environments affected and were affected by global trade, climate, and disease. From down in the mud of Egypt's canals to up in the treetops of Anatolia, Alan Mikhail tackles major aspects of the Middle East's environmental history: natural resource management, climate, human and animal labor, energy, water control, disease, and politics. He also points to some of the ways in which the region's dominant religious tradition, Islam, has understood and related to the natural world. Marrying environmental and Ottoman history, Under Osman's Tree offers a bold new interpretation of the past five hundred years of Middle Eastern history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 4aEgypt. 4aIslam. 4aOttoman Empire. 4aanimals. 4aclimate. 4adisease. 4aenergy. 4aenvironment. 4alabor. 4awater. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226427201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226427201.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles